  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Kachin Child Protection Project (KCPP)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">1) Trainings for Local Partner Organizations, Child Protection Committees, Government and adults working with children on the prevention of trafficking, unsafe migration, abuse, exploitation (prevention and resolution), violence, HIV/aids and drugs, and general Child Protection training.
2) Trainings to IDP children and youths on protection (against trafficking, exploitation, abuse, violence, drugs) and of life skills.
3) Strengthen or set up Child Protection systems and functioning within 31 IDP camps and 28 villages.
4) Basic psycho-social support for youths through group meetings, building on cultural coping mechanisms and group support.
5) Lead weekly sport, recreational or other social activities for youth (volleyball, chinlon, singing competition, special events). 
6) Provide vocational skills training for IDP youths. 
7) Provide support to families to send their children to school (e.g. uniform, caretaker to take children to school in safe way, etc).
8) Consult community members on their livelihood needs.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Kachin conflict related community based child protection project assists communities to improve their capacity to protect and support their children and youth.  KCPP establishes and manages child protection systems and ensures functioning in 31 internally displaced people (IDP) camps and 28 villages. Community based psycho-social support is accessible to IDP youths (12-18 years) to reduce the negative psycho-somatic impact of traumatic events.  Families are supported to provide sufficient care for their children (including foster), enabling children in target villages to stay with their families.</narrative>
  </description>
